00:36:57,027 --> 00:37:00,467
"If you had it once,
you can always get it back."

499
00:37:00,867 --> 00:37:05,026
Was that Dr. Tischner
or was that Dr. Hopkins?

500
00:37:06,866 --> 00:37:08,626
The one with the sibilant "S."

501
00:37:08,866 --> 00:37:09,666
Right.

502
00:37:11,186 --> 00:37:13,746
Wrong. It was a lateral lisp.

503
00:37:13,906 --> 00:37:16,546
Sex is simply a symbolic expression...

504
00:37:16,706 --> 00:37:19,586
...of the emotional status
of a relationship.

505
00:37:20,146 --> 00:37:25,026
Sustained lack of sex is
symptomatic of disassociation.

506
00:37:25,586 --> 00:37:28,386
No, the one with the lateral lisp
was Dr. Rifkin.

507
00:37:28,626 --> 00:37:32,786
Dr. Hopkins was the one with the
Rorschach birthmark on his forehead.

508
00:37:32,946 --> 00:37:36,625
It looked like California. How could
you pay attention to what he said?

509
00:37:36,865 --> 00:37:39,825
This cycle of closeness,
then estrangement...

510
00:37:40,065 --> 00:37:41,505
...you've both told me about...

511
00:37:41,745 --> 00:37:45,105
...what instigates it?
First thing that comes to your mind.

512
00:37:45,345 --> 00:37:47,505
-Sacramento.
-Governor Gray Davis.

513
00:37:47,905 --> 00:37:52,545
My personal favorite was the Freudian
with the prostate problem.

514
00:37:53,505 --> 00:37:55,185
When two people go to bed...

515
00:37:55,425 --> 00:37:58,785
...there are actually six people
in that bed.

516
00:37:59,905 --> 00:38:01,425
If you'll excuse me.

517
00:38:04,064 --> 00:38:06,224
Are we allowed to talk when he's gone?

518
00:38:06,624 --> 00:38:08,064
I don't know.

519
00:38:09,024 --> 00:38:10,304
What do you think?

520
00:38:10,624 --> 00:38:13,104
To be on the safe side,
maybe we better not.

521
00:38:20,944 --> 00:38:23,664
The six people in bed are
the two of you...

522
00:38:24,144 --> 00:38:27,264
...and your parents
and your parents.

523
00:38:28,064 --> 00:38:30,704
Now, the key is....

524
00:38:31,264 --> 00:38:32,943
Will you excuse me, please?

525
00:38:36,783 --> 00:38:39,183
He charged us for the full session.

526
00:38:39,343 --> 00:38:41,983
The man was peeing on our time!

527
00:38:45,263 --> 00:38:47,823
All that therapy was
a waste of time and money.

528
00:38:48,063 --> 00:38:50,783
Where did all that therapy
really get us?

529
00:38:51,583 --> 00:38:53,663
It got us here,
laughing about it.

530
00:38:53,903 --> 00:38:57,583
-He's right.
-Once it's broken, it can't be fixed.

531
00:38:57,823 --> 00:38:59,983
-I don't know.
-The queen has spoken.

532
00:39:00,223 --> 00:39:03,342
-Maybe it's too soon.
-What are you talking about?

533
00:39:03,582 --> 00:39:07,982
The whole point of having a fight is
playing "hide the salami" afterwards.

534
00:39:08,862 --> 00:39:11,982
Let hard times bring you together.
Nobody said it'd be easy.

535
00:39:12,222 --> 00:39:15,662
Can't hard times bring us together?
Nobody said it'd be easy.

536
00:39:15,982 --> 00:39:18,702
Like the Andrews Sisters.
After "Boogie Woogie Bugle Boy" ...

537
00:39:19,022 --> 00:39:21,022
...before "Don't Sit
Under the Apple Tree."

538
00:39:21,262 --> 00:39:23,022
Big career slump there.

539
00:39:23,262 --> 00:39:26,062
Like the Andrews Sisters before
"Don't Sit Under the Apple Tree."

540
00:39:26,302 --> 00:39:27,662
The Andrews Sisters?

541
00:39:27,982 --> 00:39:29,902
They didn't stop
because of a few flops.

542
00:39:30,142 --> 00:39:32,301
They hung in there.
The rest is history.

543
00:39:32,541 --> 00:39:34,541
Don't sit under the apple tree

544
00:39:34,941 --> 00:39:37,981
Why are you bringing up
the Andrews Sisters now?

545
00:39:38,141 --> 00:39:40,221
-You're singing!
-It's an example.

546
00:39:40,461 --> 00:39:42,541
They're in trouble,
and you're singing?

547
00:39:42,781 --> 00:39:46,621
Dot, put out once in a while.
Your face won't be so tight.

548
00:39:46,781 --> 00:39:47,661
Slut.

549
00:39:47,821 --> 00:39:52,301
I don't know what their career slump
has to do with our marital problems.

550
00:39:52,621 --> 00:39:53,981
What should we do?

551
00:39:54,221 --> 00:39:57,661
Make matters worse by dwelling
on every little thing all our lives?

552
00:39:57,901 --> 00:40:00,381
Is that what you think I do?

553
00:40:00,701 --> 00:40:03,020
-You're a child.
-I just dwell on everything?

554
00:40:03,260 --> 00:40:05,420
You're a 72-year-old infant!

555
00:40:05,660 --> 00:40:09,340
There are real problems that we
haven't even begun to deal with.

556
00:40:09,580 --> 00:40:12,700
Don't you think I know that?
What happened to you?

557
00:40:12,940 --> 00:40:15,660
What happened to that fun girl
with the pith helmet?

558
00:40:15,900 --> 00:40:19,020
You don't think I ask myself
that every day?

559
00:40:19,260 --> 00:40:22,780
You beat her out of me!
There's no room here for her!

560
00:40:22,940 --> 00:40:24,380
You think it's all fun and games.

561
00:40:24,620 --> 00:40:27,500
So it's my fault you hang on
to every little thing!

562
00:40:27,820 --> 00:40:30,300
It's my fault you can't
let go of anything!

563
00:40:31,260 --> 00:40:33,899
It's my fault you turned
into your mother?!

564
00:40:34,139 --> 00:40:35,739
Fuck you!

565
00:41:22,138 --> 00:41:26,138
-I still think that there's a chance--
-Ben, you love who we were.

566
00:41:26,378 --> 00:41:29,658
You couldn't possibly love
what we've become.

567
00:41:30,618 --> 00:41:32,857
I think I spotted us
at dinner tonight.

568
00:41:34,857 --> 00:41:37,577
We can't stay together
just because we...

569
00:41:37,817 --> 00:41:40,377
...get a glimpse of "us"
every once in a while.

570
00:41:40,937 --> 00:41:43,017
It was less than 1 5 minutes ago.

571
00:41:44,937 --> 00:41:48,297
All we proved is, if we're apart
for weeks at a time...

572
00:41:48,457 --> 00:41:51,337
...we might get through a dinner.
That's not a marriage.

573
00:41:57,497 --> 00:41:58,857
It's over.

574
00:42:36,775 --> 00:42:38,055
A book about your grandmother?

575
00:42:38,215 --> 00:42:40,375
Yeah. She was an extraordinary woman.

576
00:42:40,615 --> 00:42:43,495
I'm sure she was.
Did she fuck a President?

577
00:42:44,695 --> 00:42:47,735
No. Did she discover uranium?

578
00:42:47,895 --> 00:42:50,215
A cure for cancer?
Nothing like that?

579
00:42:51,255 --> 00:42:54,215
Why would anybody wanna read
a book about her?

580
00:42:54,535 --> 00:42:57,975
She was 4'9" . She emigrated
from Europe as a little girl.

581
00:42:58,215 --> 00:43:02,374
She worked in a sweatshop making
buttonholes 14 hours a day and yet...

582
00:43:02,614 --> 00:43:06,454
...raised five kids and stayed married
to the same man for 57 years.

583
00:43:06,614 --> 00:43:09,734
Dave, this will be the greatest
love story ever told.

584
00:43:11,254 --> 00:43:14,294
Let me explain something to you.
Not as your agent.

585
00:43:14,534 --> 00:43:16,294
This is as a friend.

586
00:43:20,854 --> 00:43:22,134
Come here.

587
00:43:23,254 --> 00:43:24,774
You see all these people?

588
00:43:25,094 --> 00:43:28,054
They're getting into buildings.
They're driving cars.

589
00:43:28,294 --> 00:43:31,093
They're crossing the street.
They're walking around.

590
00:43:31,573 --> 00:43:33,813
Every single one of these people...

591
00:43:34,053 --> 00:43:36,133
...is going to die someday...

592
00:43:36,293 --> 00:43:37,733
...and they all know it.

593
00:43:39,093 --> 00:43:40,373
Which is why...

594
00:43:41,173 --> 00:43:44,533
...they regard the time they have
on this planet as precious.

595
00:43:44,853 --> 00:43:47,173
There are things that take up
that time...

596
00:43:47,413 --> 00:43:50,453
...even if they don't enjoy it.
They have to go to work.

597
00:43:50,693 --> 00:43:53,013
They have to get dressed,
wait in lines...

598
00:43:53,253 --> 00:43:55,573
...clean yards, get batteries.

599
00:43:55,813 --> 00:43:58,933
They visit the eye doctor.
They're doing all these things.

600
00:43:59,173 --> 00:44:04,052
Now, add that to the time they spend
sleeping and eating...

601
00:44:04,212 --> 00:44:07,092
...and washing up and voting...

602
00:44:07,412 --> 00:44:10,692
...and buying gifts for people
they don't like, and you see...

603
00:44:11,012 --> 00:44:14,772
...why they're so choosy about
how they spend their leisure time.

604
00:44:15,012 --> 00:44:18,292
You can understand why
unless she went down on somebody...

605
00:44:18,452 --> 00:44:22,132
...really interesting, they won't
waste their valuable time...

606
00:44:22,372 --> 00:44:25,812
...reading a book about
your fucking grandmother!

607
00:44:28,452 --> 00:44:31,091
So if I read you right,
you don't like the idea.

608
00:44:31,491 --> 00:44:32,531
It's not that.

609
00:44:43,411 --> 00:44:47,251
You know, I find the Ariana
much more fragrant than the Raphaela.

610
00:44:49,251 --> 00:44:50,851
I'll keep that in mind.

611
00:44:51,011 --> 00:44:53,171
-How you doing?
-Fine.

612
00:44:53,411 --> 00:44:57,011
I never got a chance to thank you
for holding the camp bus.

613
00:44:57,171 --> 00:44:59,890
Anytime you need a bus held,
I am your guy.

614
00:45:00,130 --> 00:45:03,090
-Erin's teeth are looking good.
-Thanks to you.

615
00:45:03,330 --> 00:45:05,730
I hope she remembers to wear
her retainer.

616
00:45:06,130 --> 00:45:07,730
You know how kids are at camp.

617
00:45:08,050 --> 00:45:11,730
The minute my Kevin gets off that bus,
it's "Goodbye, biteplate."

618
00:45:12,130 --> 00:45:13,650
Is that for you?

619
00:45:15,330 --> 00:45:18,770
When Deirdre and I divorced,
I decided to learn how to cook.

620
00:45:19,010 --> 00:45:21,090
The Wok-y World of Thai Cooking?

621
00:45:21,410 --> 00:45:22,610
I'm branching out.

622
00:45:22,850 --> 00:45:25,730
I'm taking a Thai cooking course
this summer.

623
00:45:25,970 --> 00:45:29,250
Really? I've always been interested
in Asian cooking.

624
00:45:29,409 --> 00:45:30,609
Really?

625
00:45:31,089 --> 00:45:32,449
Why don't you join me?

626
00:45:35,089 --> 00:45:36,849
When I think about it...

627
00:45:37,249 --> 00:45:39,809
...over the years there were
less and less moments...

628
00:45:39,969 --> 00:45:41,489
...in the course of the day...

629
00:45:41,809 --> 00:45:44,529
...when Ben and I actually made
real eye contact.

630
00:45:44,769 --> 00:45:47,329
You are not gonna believe
what happened.

631
00:45:47,569 --> 00:45:50,049
-What?
-He's almost asleep.

632
00:45:51,569 --> 00:45:53,569
Maybe it was the stuff of life.

633
00:45:53,969 --> 00:45:55,809
Who's taking Erin to school?

634
00:45:56,449 --> 00:45:59,408
Who will pick up Josh
from his clarinet lessons?

635
00:46:00,048 --> 00:46:02,448
After a while, there was
a disturbing comfort...

636
00:46:02,768 --> 00:46:04,768
...in not having to deal
with each other...

637
00:46:05,088 --> 00:46:08,848
...because somehow you just
get used to the disconnection.

638
00:46:09,728 --> 00:46:13,728
Even at night, when we could finally
come together, we faced forward.

639
00:46:13,888 --> 00:46:16,928
Yeah, we were tired,
but I think we were afraid...

640
00:46:17,248 --> 00:46:20,528
...that if we faced each other,
there'd be nothing there.

641
00:46:20,928 --> 00:46:22,928
We're learning Mee Krob next week.

642
00:46:23,408 --> 00:46:24,768
Mee Krob.

643
00:46:26,048 --> 00:46:27,808
I'll let you know.

644
00:46:31,647 --> 00:46:34,287
I'll call you. Oh, you call me.

645
00:46:39,647 --> 00:46:42,287
When we drove to the camp
for Parents' Weekend...

646
00:46:42,527 --> 00:46:44,607
...I was scared to face the kids.

647
00:46:45,247 --> 00:46:49,567
You'd talk about it with a best friend.
But Katie had been my best friend.

648
00:46:49,807 --> 00:46:53,967
Now I didn't know what we were,
except Josh and Erin's parents.

649
00:47:20,766 --> 00:47:21,966
What?

650
00:47:23,726 --> 00:47:25,086
Nothing.

651
00:47:27,966 --> 00:47:29,565
--is nothing?

652
00:47:31,085 --> 00:47:33,325
This is not going to be easy.

653
00:47:34,765 --> 00:47:37,805
The kids do not need to be burdened
with our problems.

654
00:47:38,045 --> 00:47:39,805
They have half a summer left.

655
00:47:40,045 --> 00:47:42,845
Like my plan was to burden
the kids with our problems.

656
00:47:43,005 --> 00:47:46,285
Jesus Christ, will you give me
some fucking credit?

657
00:47:53,165 --> 00:47:54,365
I missed you.

658
00:47:54,845 --> 00:47:56,525
I missed you so much.

659
00:47:56,845 --> 00:47:58,524
I missed you both so much.

660
00:48:01,724 --> 00:48:03,484
Dad, pull yourself together.

661
00:48:03,884 --> 00:48:05,964
Dad, get off of me!

662
00:48:07,724 --> 00:48:10,604
You guys both look terrific!
Show us your bunks.

663
00:48:11,564 --> 00:48:13,244
I wanna see your bunks too.

664
00:48:13,484 --> 00:48:16,204
Did you get your favorite room?
The Acorn Cabin?

665
00:48:16,444 --> 00:48:17,804
Yeah, we did.

666
00:48:18,044 --> 00:48:20,124
We got the Acorn Cabin.

667
00:49:07,402 --> 00:49:09,002
God, I hate lying to them.

668
00:49:09,242 --> 00:49:11,882
Me too. We're not even good at it.

669
00:49:12,122 --> 00:49:14,762
Even if we were good at it,
they'd still know.

670
00:49:38,521 --> 00:49:39,721
What is that?

671
00:49:40,281 --> 00:49:41,161
What's what?

672
00:49:41,481 --> 00:49:44,681
-The thing you just put in your mouth.
-It's my biteplate.

673
00:49:44,841 --> 00:49:47,961
-Biteplate?
-Yeah. It's my biteplate.

674
00:49:48,201 --> 00:49:50,921
-Why do you have a biteplate?
-For my bite.

675
00:49:52,041 --> 00:49:53,401
What's wrong with your bite?

676
00:49:54,521 --> 00:49:56,201
It's askew.

677
00:49:56,361 --> 00:49:57,240
Askew?

678
00:49:57,480 --> 00:49:59,160
Yes, it's askew.

679
00:49:59,800 --> 00:50:02,920
So this would be an attempt
to de-skew it?

680
00:50:08,440 --> 00:50:10,200
You order room service?

681
00:50:17,960 --> 00:50:20,120
-What's the matter?
-Nothing. I'm okay.

682
00:50:20,360 --> 00:50:21,640
Honey, are you okay?

683
00:50:21,880 --> 00:50:23,800
I'm okay. I'm fine.

684
00:50:24,040 --> 00:50:27,239
I couldn't sleep, so
I snuck out after lights out.

685
00:50:27,639 --> 00:50:30,039
I just wanted to sleep
with you guys.

686
00:50:32,439 --> 00:50:36,279
It's okay. I'll call the camp
and let them know you're here.

687
00:50:41,319 --> 00:50:43,559
Why is the bed made up on the couch?

688
00:50:45,639 --> 00:50:49,399
Daddy was doing a little reading,
and I didn't wanna wake Mommy up.

689
00:51:22,278 --> 00:51:25,238
Sometimes you just can't
climb out of the abyss.

690
00:51:25,958 --> 00:51:28,197
I thought of last summer,
when we still hoped...

691
00:51:28,437 --> 00:51:31,397
...that if we put ourselves
in some idyllic setting...

692
00:51:31,557 --> 00:51:34,117
...we'd somehow get rid
of all the tension...

693
00:51:34,357 --> 00:51:35,877
...jump-start our marriage...

694
00:51:36,117 --> 00:51:39,237
...and rediscover why we fell in love
in the first place.

695
00:51:39,397 --> 00:51:41,637
So last year,
after Parents' Weekend...

696
00:51:41,797 --> 00:51:44,437
...we thought maybe
in a trattoria in Venice...

697
00:51:44,757 --> 00:51:48,277
...looking at a beautiful sunset,
next to a bottle of Chianti...

698
00:51:48,437 --> 00:51:51,237
...we just might find a set
of jumper cables.

699
00:51:53,077 --> 00:51:55,797
How you doing?
Two Italian ices, please.

700
00:51:56,116 --> 00:52:00,116
Honey, you don't have to say Italian.
We're here. They know.

701
00:52:00,436 --> 00:52:04,276
So if I'm in Belgium, and I order
a Belgian waffle, I just say waffle?

702
00:52:04,516 --> 00:52:07,716
Like if you were in Ireland
and you wanted Irish stew...

703
00:52:07,876 --> 00:52:09,396
...you'd just say stew.

704
00:52:09,636 --> 00:52:12,196
If you're in China and
you want Chinese food...

705
00:52:12,436 --> 00:52:14,196
...you say, "Bring on the food."

706
00:52:15,316 --> 00:52:18,436
We couldn't help but overhear
your delightful repartee.

707
00:52:18,676 --> 00:52:21,156
We're the Kirbys from Cleveland.
And you are...?

708
00:52:21,396 --> 00:52:23,636
-The Mansons.
-From Spawn Ranch.

709
00:52:27,875 --> 00:52:28,995
That's a good one.

710
00:52:44,995 --> 00:52:46,995
Look, sweetie. There.
The red cape.

711
00:52:47,235 --> 00:52:48,515
I like that.

712
00:52:54,355 --> 00:52:55,315
It's you...

713
00:52:55,554 --> 00:52:56,354
...people.

714
00:52:56,674 --> 00:52:59,714
-The Kirbys from Cleveland.
-Joanie and Eddie.

715
00:52:59,954 --> 00:53:03,234
How could we forget?
We haven't stopped talking about you.

716
00:53:03,714 --> 00:53:06,754
This is fate. We have to
get together, break bread.

717
00:53:06,914 --> 00:53:09,714
Sounds great.
We're at the Hotel Pasta e Fagioli.

718
00:53:10,834 --> 00:53:13,234
You call us.
We're at the Europa Regina.

719
00:53:13,474 --> 00:53:15,714
Great. We'll call you.

720
00:53:15,954 --> 00:53:17,074
Oh, right on!

721
00:53:19,714 --> 00:53:20,594
Look at this.

722
00:53:20,834 --> 00:53:22,674
-This is beautiful.
-This way.

723
00:53:22,994 --> 00:53:25,074
-Thank you.
-Canal-side seating.

724
00:53:25,313 --> 00:53:26,673
Very nice.

725
00:53:29,233 --> 00:53:31,153
Oh, my God!

726
00:53:32,193 --> 00:53:33,633
Meant to be!

727
00:53:34,593 --> 00:53:36,593
Kismet! Kismet!

728
00:53:36,993 --> 00:53:40,833
We went looking for your hotel,
but we couldn't find it anywhere.

729
00:53:41,073 --> 00:53:44,993
-Yeah, it's pretty hard to find.
-Well, all's well that ends well.

730
00:53:47,233 --> 00:53:50,673
It was just like fate,
the first time I met Joanie.

731
00:53:50,913 --> 00:53:54,433
I worked on the 6th floor,
and Eddie worked on the 4th floor.

732
00:53:54,753 --> 00:53:56,992
-Hand to God.
-Every day in the cafeteria...

733
00:53:57,232 --> 00:53:59,712
-...on the third floor--
-I saw Joanie at the salad bar.

734
00:53:59,952 --> 00:54:02,352
And she smiled at me.
Not just a smile.

735
00:54:02,592 --> 00:54:04,512
I mean, a really big smile.

736
00:54:05,312 --> 00:54:07,872
One day at the salad bar
at Beefsteak Charlie's...

737
00:54:08,192 --> 00:54:10,512
...I thought I saw her
at that salad bar.

738
00:54:10,752 --> 00:54:13,232
-But it wasn't me.
-It wasn't Joanie!

739
00:54:14,112 --> 00:54:18,112
What are the odds of another person
at a salad bar looking like Joanie...

740
00:54:18,352 --> 00:54:20,192
...and yet not being Joanie?

741
00:54:20,992 --> 00:54:23,312
What, like a trillion to one?

742
00:54:23,552 --> 00:54:25,311
Could be higher than that.

743
00:54:25,551 --> 00:54:29,551
Anyway, when I realized it wasn't
Joanie, I was so disappointed.

744
00:54:29,791 --> 00:54:33,791
And I began to think about how much
I'd hoped that it was Joanie.

745
00:54:34,031 --> 00:54:36,431
But at this point
you still hadn't met.

746
00:54:36,671 --> 00:54:41,391
No. And I couldn't get over how much
I wanted this person to be Joanie.

747
00:54:41,631 --> 00:54:44,511
And I think that was
the defining moment.

748
00:54:44,751 --> 00:54:47,951
I went back to my wife at the table
at Beefsteak Charlie's...

749
00:54:48,271 --> 00:54:52,191
...and I realized I felt more alive
thinking about that stranger...

750
00:54:52,431 --> 00:54:56,350
...I thought was Joanie than I did
with the stranger who was my wife.

751
00:54:56,590 --> 00:54:58,830
We were both in marriages
we'd outgrown.

752
00:54:59,070 --> 00:55:01,950
You know, maybe I didn't
wanna admit it, but maybe...

753
00:55:02,110 --> 00:55:05,790
...I didn't like myself enough
to be with someone who liked me.

754
00:55:06,030 --> 00:55:08,910
Can you imagine anybody
not liking Eddie Kirby?

755
00:55:09,150 --> 00:55:11,150
I'm not so perfect.

756
00:55:11,390 --> 00:55:12,990
Beg to differ!

757
00:55:13,310 --> 00:55:18,190
That year we both mustered up
enough courage to leave our marriages.

758
00:55:18,510 --> 00:55:20,350
So at this point you had met.

759
00:55:21,470 --> 00:55:22,350
Still hadn't met.

760
00:55:23,230 --> 00:55:27,149
But, you know, after you've had
such a horrible marriage...

761
00:55:27,469 --> 00:55:30,349
...you don't wanna make
the same mistakes twice.

762
00:55:30,589 --> 00:55:32,989
So I made an inner pact with myself.

763
00:55:33,229 --> 00:55:36,749
I said, "Eddie, you will never
let anger build up to the point...

764
00:55:36,989 --> 00:55:38,829
...where you don't like
your partner."

765
00:55:39,149 --> 00:55:41,469
-I made the same pact.
-That became our credo.

766
00:55:41,789 --> 00:55:44,349
"Never go to bed angry."

767
00:55:44,909 --> 00:55:47,149
So now we talk everything through.

768
00:55:47,389 --> 00:55:50,989
We won't let even the tiniest pea
be under our mattress.

769
00:55:51,229 --> 00:55:53,629
That's why we never eat in bed.

770
00:55:57,388 --> 00:55:59,148
Me too.

771
00:56:02,428 --> 00:56:04,268
Who'd have thought the Kirbys...

772
00:56:04,428 --> 00:56:06,828
...the happiest couple
never to have met...

773
00:56:06,988 --> 00:56:10,028
...would be the greatest
aphrodisiac known to man?

774
00:56:35,387 --> 00:56:38,347
If only you could bottle
that unfettered state of mind...

775
00:56:38,587 --> 00:56:40,587
...that comes with being
on foreign soil...

776
00:56:41,067 --> 00:56:42,587
...to just hold on to it...

777
00:56:42,827 --> 00:56:45,387
...even for a day, an evening...

778
00:56:46,107 --> 00:56:47,467
...an hour.

779
00:56:47,867 --> 00:56:50,907
Last year, when we
got back from Italy, God knows...

780
00:56:51,147 --> 00:56:52,987
...we gave it a try.

781
00:57:07,946 --> 00:57:09,386
Hey, look at this.

782
00:57:09,946 --> 00:57:14,106
